# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: typeorm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:typeorm/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] In software engineering, the **data mapper pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Create, Read, Update, and Delete, that operate on objects that represent domain entity types in a data store.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] A Data Mapper is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] The goal of the pattern is to keep the in-memory representation and the persistent data store independent of each other and the data mapper itself.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] This is useful when one needs to model and enforce strict business processes on the data in the domain layer that do not map neatly to the persistent data store.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] The layer is composed of one or more mappers (or Data Access Objects), performing the data transfer.
[src:typeorm/data-mapper-pattern] Generic mappers will handle many different domain entity types; dedicated mappers will handle one or a few.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:typeorm/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Supports both DataMapper and ActiveRecord patterns, giving you the flexibility to choose what works best for your project.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Built from the ground up with TypeScript support, providing complete type safety for your database models.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Works with MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, SQLite, MS SQL Server, Oracle, MongoDB, and more.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Elegant syntax for building complex queries with joins, pagination, and caching.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] First-class support for database migrations with automatic generation.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Works in Node.js, browsers, mobile, and desktop applications.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] TypeORM provides a beautiful, simple API for interacting with your database that takes full advantage of TypeScript's type system.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Choose between DataMapper and ActiveRecord patterns - both are fully supported.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] All logos are trademarks of their respective owners, used for identification purposes only.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] TypeORM runs in NodeJS, Browser, Cordova, Ionic, React Native, NativeScript, Expo, and Electron platforms.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] TypeORM makes database interaction a breeze.
[src:typeorm/typeorm-io] Join thousands of developers who are already building better applications with TypeORM.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:typeorm/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:typeorm/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:typeorm/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:typeorm/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:typeorm/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:typeorm/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:typeorm/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:typeorm/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:typeorm/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:typeorm/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:typeorm/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:typeorm/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:typeorm/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:typeorm/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:typeorm/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:typeorm/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:typeorm/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:typeorm/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:typeorm/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:typeorm/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:typeorm/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
